entries.meaning: An order for too much or too many.
(mathematics) A ring for which a specified subring R contains no nonempty socles and for which any R-module is of finite length.

verbs.description: overorder (third-person singular simple present overorders, present participle overordering, simple past and past participle overordered)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To order too much or too many.
examples: Having overordered the unpopular new toys, we were forced to sell them at a discount.
